[Kennebec River]]. The city is home to [[Colby College]] and [[Thomas College]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] the population was 15,722,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2380740| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001), Waterville city, Maine| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American FactFinder| accessdate=March 7, 2019| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213045311/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US2380740| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref>  and in 2018 the estimated population was 16,646.<ref name=\"USCensusQuickFacts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/watervillecitymaine|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Waterville city, Maine|website=Census Bureau QuickFacts|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref> Along with [[Augusta, Maine|Augusta]], Waterville is one of the principal cities of the [[Augusta-Waterville, ME Micropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nThe area now known as Waterville was once inhabited by the Canibas tribe of the [[Abenaki]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|people]]. Called \"Taconnet\" after Chief Taconnet, the main village was located on the east bank of the Kennebec River at its confluence with the [[Sebasticook River]] at what is now [[Winslow, Maine|Winslow]]. Known as \"Ticonic\" by [[British colonization of the Americas|English settlers]], it was burned in 1692 during [[King William's War]], after which the Canibas tribe abandoned the area. [[Fort Halifax (Maine)|Fort Halifax]] was built by General [[John Winslow (British Army officer)|John Winslow]] in 1754, and the last skirmish with indigenous peoples occurred on May 18, 1757.<ref name=\"Events in Waterville History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.watervillemaine.net/history/history.html|title=History in Waterville, Maine -|website=Watervillemaine.net|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe township would be organized as Kingfield Plantation, then incorporated as [[Winslow, Maine|Winslow]] in 1771. When residents on the west side of the Kennebec found themselves unable to cross the river to attend [[town meeting]]s, Waterville was founded from the western parts of Winslow and incorporated on June 23, 1802. In 1824 a bridge was built joining the communities. Early industries included [[fishing]], [[lumbering]], [[agriculture]] and [[ship building]], with larger boats launched in spring during [[freshet]]s. By the early 1900s, there were five shipyards in the community.<ref name=Coolidge>{{Cite book| last = Coolidge| first = Austin J.| author2=John B. Mansfield| title = A History and Description of New England| year = 1859| location = Boston, Massachusetts| pages = 344\u2013345| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OcoMAAAAYAAJ&dq=A%20History%20and%20Description%20of%20New%20England%20Coolidge%20Mansfield&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nTiconic Falls blocked navigation farther upriver, so Waterville developed as the terminus for trade and shipping. The Kennebec River and Messalonskee Stream provided [[water power]] for mills, including several [[sawmill]]s, a [[gristmill]], a [[window sash|sash]] and [[window shutter|blind]] factory, a furniture factory, and a shovel handle factory. There was also a carriage and sleigh factory, boot shop, [[brickmaking|brickyard]], and [[Tanning (leather)|tannery]]. On September 27, 1849, the [[Androscoggin and Kennebec Railroad]] opened to Waterville. It would become part of the [[Maine Central Railroad]], which in 1870 established [[locomotive]] and car repair shops in the thriving [[mill town]]. West Waterville (renamed [[Oakland, Maine|Oakland]]) was set off as a town in 1873. Waterville was incorporated as a city on January 12, 1888.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Varney\n  | first = George J.\n  | title = Gazetteer of the state of Maine. Waterville\n  | place = Boston\n  | publisher = Russell\n  | year = 1886\n  | url = http://history.rays-place.com/me/waterville-me.htm }}\n</ref>\n\nThe Ticonic Water Power & Manufacturing Company was formed in 1866 and soon built a dam across the Kennebec. After a change of ownership in 1873, the company began construction on what would become the Lockwood Manufacturing Company, a [[cotton]] textile plant. A second mill was added, and by 1900 the firm dominated the riverfront and employed 1,300 workers. Lockwood Mills survived until the mid-1950s. The iron [[Two Cent Bridge|Waterville-Winslow Footbridge]] opened in 1901, as a means for Waterville residents to commute to Winslow for work in the [[Hollingsworth & Whitney Company|Hollingsworth & Whitney Co.]] and Wyandotte Worsted Co. mills, but in less than a year was carried away by the highest river level since 1832. Rebuilt in 1903, it would be called the Two Cent Bridge because of its [[toll road|toll]].<ref name=\"Plocher\"/> In 1902, the [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style City Hall and Opera House designed by George Gilman Adams was dedicated. In 2002, the [[C.F. Hathaway Company]], one of the last remaining factories in the United States producing high-end [[dress shirt]]s, was purchased by Warren Buffett's [[Berkshire Hathaway]] company and was closed after over 160 years of operation in the city.<ref name=\"Plocher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.waterville-me.gov/content/1233260491webhistory.pdf|author=Stephen Plocher|title=\"A Short History of Waterville, Maine\" (2007)|date=|website=Waterville-me.gov|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nWaterville also developed as an educational center. In 1813, the [[Maine Literary and Theological Institution]] was established. It would be renamed Waterville College in 1821, then [[Colby College]] in 1867. [[Thomas College]] was established in 1894. The Latin School was founded in 1820 to prepare students to attend Colby and other colleges, and was subsequently named Waterville Academy, Waterville Classical Institute, and Coburn Classical Institute; the Institute merged with the Oak Grove School in [[Vassalboro, Maine|Vassalboro]] in 1970, and remained open until the 1980s. The first public high school was built in 1877, while the current Waterville Senior High School was built in 1961.<ref name=\"Events in Waterville History\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nWaterville is located in northern Kennebec County at {{Coord|44.552051|-69.645839|type:city_region:US-ME|format=dms|display=inline}}.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Its northern boundary is the [[Somerset County, Maine|Somerset County]] line.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|14.05|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|13.58|sqmi|sqkm|2}} are land and {{convert|0.47|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, or 3.36%, are water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-01-25}}</ref> Situated beside the [[Kennebec River]], Waterville is drained by the Messalonskee Stream.\n\nWaterville is served by [[Interstate 95 in Maine|Interstate 95]], [[U.S. Route 201]], and Maine State Routes [[Maine State Route 137|137]] and [[Maine State Route 104|104]]. It is bordered by [[Fairfield, Maine|Fairfield]] on the north in Somerset County, [[Winslow, Maine|Winslow]] on the east, [[Sidney, Maine|Sidney]] on the south and [[Oakland, Maine|Oakland]] on the west.\n\n===Climate===\nThis [[climate|climatic]] region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Waterville has a [[humid continental climate]], abbreviated \"Dfb\" on climate maps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=87937&cityname=Waterville%2C+Maine%2C+United+States+of+America&units=|title=Waterville, Maine K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|work=Weatherbase}}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"width:85%;\">\n{{Weather box\n|location = Waterville, Maine\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  58\n|Feb record high F =  61\n|Mar record high F =  84\n|Apr record high F =  91\n|May record high F =  98\n|Jun record high F = 96\n|Jul record high F =  96\n|Aug record high F = 101\n|Sep record high F =  96\n|Oct record high F =  84\n|Nov record high F =  73\n|Dec record high F =  67\n|year record high F= 101\n|Jan high F = 29.8\n|Feb high F = 33.5\n|Mar high F = 42.5\n|Apr high F = 55.2\n|May high F = 67.9\n|Jun high F = 76.4\n|Jul high F = 81.3\n|Aug high F = 80.1\n|Sep high F = 71.8\n|Oct high F = 59.8\n|Nov high F = 46.7\n|Dec high F = 34.3\n|year high F=\n|Jan low F = 7.8\n|Feb low F = 9.7\n|Mar low F = 20.8\n|Apr low F = 31.7\n|May low F = 42.3\n|Jun low F = 52.1\n|Jul low F = 57.6\n|Aug low F = 56.1\n|Sep low F = 47.9\n|Oct low F = 37.5\n|Nov low F = 28.7\n|Dec low F = 15.2\n|year low F=\n|Jan record low F = \u221232\n|Feb record low F = \u221231\n|Mar record low F = \u221217\n|Apr record low F = 8\n|May record low F =  21\n|Jun record low F =  34\n|Jul record low F =  39\n|Aug record low F =  35\n|Sep record low F =  23\n|Oct record low F =  17\n|Nov record low F =   \u22121\n|Dec record low F = \u221227\n|year record low F=  \n|Jan precipitation inch = 2.87\n|Feb precipitation inch = 2.54\n|Mar precipitation inch = 3.23\n|Apr precipitation inch = 3.49\n|May precipitation inch = 3.51\n|Jun precipitation inch = 3.65\n|Jul precipitation inch = 3.45\n|Aug precipitation inch = 3.53\n|Sep precipitation inch = 3.57\n|Oct precipitation inch = 4.21\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.17\n|Dec precipitation inch = 3.58\n|year precipitation inch =  \n|source = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?me9151|title=Waterville Pump Stn, Maine - Climate Summary}}</ref>\n}}\n</div>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1810= 1314\n|1820= 1719\n|1830= 2216\n|1840= 2971\n|1850= 3964\n|1860= 4390\n|1870= 4852\n|1880= 4672\n|1890= 7107\n|1900= 9477\n|1910= 11458\n|1920= 13351\n|1930= 15454\n|1940= 16688\n|1950= 18287\n|1960= 18695\n|1970= 18192\n|1980= 17779\n|1990= 17173\n|2000= 15605\n|2010= 15722\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=16646\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusQuickFacts\"/>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|website=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Image:Junction of Silver & Elm Streets, Waterville, ME.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Silver and Elm streets (1910), showing the [[Universalist-Unitarian Church|Universalist Church]], which was established in 1832]]\n[[File:Waterville, ME population, since 2000.jpeg|thumb|left|Population of Waterville from 2000 to 2015]]\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212234628/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-23}}</ref> of 2010, there were 15,722 people, 6,370 households, and 3,274 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1157.7|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 7,065 housing units at an average density of {{convert|520.3|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 93.9% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 1.1% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.6% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.2% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.8% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 2.4% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.4% of the population.\n\nThere were 6,370 households of which 24.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 32.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 13.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.8% had a male householder with no wife present, and 48.6% were non-families. Of all households 38.9% were made up of individuals and 15.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.13 and the average family size was 2.80.\n\nThe median age in the city was 36.8 years. 17.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 18.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 21.7% were from 25 to 44; 24.7% were from 45 to 64; and 16.7% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 46.8% male and 53.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 15,605 people, 6,218 households, and 3,370 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,148.7 people per square mile (443.3/km\u00b2). There were 6,819 housing units at an average density of 501.9 per square mile (193.7/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 95.81% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.78% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.56% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.03% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.03% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.42% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.36% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.10% of the population. 32% reported French and French Canadian ancestry, 18% English, 11% Irish, and 6% German.\n\nThere are 6,218 [[household]]s out of which 26.3% have children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 12.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.8% were non-families. Of all households 38.6% were made up of individuals and 16.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.13 and the average family size was 2.84.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 19.7% under the age of 18, 18.5% from 18 to 24, 24.1% from 25 to 44, 19.5% from 45 to 64, and 18.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 85.0 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 81.7 males.\n\n[[Image:Coburn Classical Institute, Waterville, ME.jpg|thumb|right|Coburn Classical Institute (c. 1910), burned in 1955]]\nThe median income for a household in the city was $26,816, and the median income for a family was $38,052. Males had a median income of $30,086 versus $22,037 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $16,430. 19.2% of the population and 15.1% of families were below the federal [[poverty]] level.  Statewide, 10.9% of the population was below the poverty level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maine.gov/spo/economics/economics/pdf/povertyreport2005.pdf |title=2005 Report Card on Poverty|website=Maine.gov|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>  In Kennebec County, 11.1% of the population was below the federal poverty level.  Thus, although the county poverty rate is close to the state poverty rate, the poverty rate for Waterville is higher\u2014typical for a regional center whose suburbs have grown in population.\n\nOut of the total population, 29.7% of those under the age of 18 and 14.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.\n\n==Economy and Redevelopment==\n{{update|section|date=November 2011|reason=needs info on the opening of the Hathaway creative Center, and the opening of MGH offices there.}}\nLike many other towns in Maine and in the United States, Waterville has seen development in the suburbs and the decline of the downtown area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maine.gov/spo/landuse/pubs/svccenters.php|title=Maine.gov|website=Main.gov|accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref> There have been new businesses and new facilities built by [http://www.inlandhospital.org Inland Hospital] on Kennedy Memorial Drive. [[Walmart]], [[Home Depot]], and a small strip mall of other stores have been built in the northern part of the city as part of an open-air shopping center. Because of this growth, the existing and now-neighboring Elm Plaza shopping center has recently had its exterior renovated and filled most or all of its previous vacancies.\n\nIn contrast, the downtown area has had its share of hardships due to chain store growth in the city. Stores that had a long history in the downtown area have closed in recent decades, including Levine's, Butlers, Sterns, Dunhams, Alvina and Delias, and LaVerdieres. The large vacancy in The Concourse shopping center that once housed the [[Ames Department Stores Inc.|Ames]], [[Zayre]] department store, as well as [[Brooks Pharmacy]] is struggling to find tenants; as is the now vacant Main Street location of a [[CVS Caremark Corporation|CVS]] pharmacy (it moved to a brand new building on Kennedy Memorial Drive).<ref>[http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/4321689.html Marketing the Concourse<br />Waterville's downtown center faces growing challenges<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520041635/http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/4321689.html |date=2009-05-20 }}</ref> Organizations like [https://web.archive.org/web/20071230021208/http://www.watervillemainstreet.org/ Waterville Main St] continue their efforts to revitalize downtown.\n\nDeveloper Paul Boghossian has converted the old Hathaway Mill to retail, office, and residential use.<ref>[http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/3072987.shtml Hathaway center plans to be unveiled tonight at council meeting<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520041949/http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/3072987.shtml |date=2009-05-20 }}</ref> MaineGeneral Health agreed at the end of June 2007 to become the first tenant.<ref>[http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/4321848.html Urban renewal spurred project<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519232223/http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/news/local/4321848.html |date=2009-05-19 }}</ref>\n\nWaterville's top employers include MaineGeneral Medical Center, Colby College, HealthReach Network, Northern Light Inland Hospital, [[Hannaford Brothers Company|Hannaford Supermarket]], [[L.L.Bean|LL Bean]], [[Maine Central Railroad Company|Central Maine Railroad]], [[Shaw's Supermarket|Shaw\u2019s Supermarket]], [[Walmart|Wal-Mart]], Affiliated Healthcare Systems, Mount St. Joseph Nursing Home, Kennebec Valley Community Action Program, Care & Comfort Healthcare Temps, Thomas College, City of Waterville, The Woodlands Residential Care, and [[Morning Sentinel|Central Maine Newspapers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://midmainechamber.com/cms/our-region/industry/|title=Industry|website=Mid-Maine Chamber of Commerce|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n===Local government===\n[[File:Waterville, ME City Hall (2014) IMG_2652.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Waterville City Hall (2014)]]\nWaterville has a [[mayor]] and [[council-manager]] form of government, led by a mayor and a seven-member city council. The city council is the governing board, and the city manager is the chief administrative officer of the city, responsible for the management of all city affairs.\n\nWaterville adopted a [[city charter]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"WardEliminating\">Rachel Ohm, [https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/12/13/waterville-city-manager-responds-to-criticism-about-idea-of-eliminating-wards/ Waterville city manager responds to criticism about idea of eliminating wards], ''Morning Sentinel'' (December 13, 2018).</ref> For some 40 years, the city had a \"[[strong mayor]]\" system in which the mayor enjoyed broad executive powers, including the power to veto measures passed by the city council and to [[line-item veto]] budget items passed by the council.<ref name=\"Palmer\">Kenneth T. Palmer, ''Maine Politics and Government'' (University of Nebraska Press, 2009), p. 205.</ref> In 2005, the charter was substantially revised, changing the city government to a \"[[weak mayor]]\" [[Council\u2013manager government|council-manager system]].<ref name=\"Palmer\"/><ref>Amy Calder, [https://www.centralmaine.com/2012/11/29/tasks-await-new-charter-panel_2012-11-29/ Waterville city political partisanship, ward system likely charter commission targets], ''Kennebec Journal'' (November 29, 2012).</ref> Under the present system, the [[city manager]] is the chief executive.<ref name=\"Palmer\"/> The charter revision was approved by city voters by a 4-1 margin.<ref name=\"Palmer\"/> The city is currently divided into seven geographic [[Ward (electoral subdivision)|wards]], each of which elects one member of the Waterville City Council and one member of the Waterville School Board.<ref name=\"WardEliminating\"/>\n\nSince 1970, the following people have served as mayor of Waterville: [[Richard Carey (politician)|Richard \"Spike\" Carey]] (1970-1978), Paul Laverdiere (Republican, 1978-1982); Ann Gilbride Hill (Democrat, 1982-1986); Thomas Nale (1986-1987); [[Judy Kany|Judy C. Kany]] (Democrat, 1988-1989); David E. Bernier (1990-1993); Thomas J. Brazier (1994-1995); Nelson Megna (1995-1996); Ruth Joseph (Democrat, 1996-1998); [[Nelson Madore]] (Democrat, 1999-2004); [[Paul R. LePage]] (Republican, 2004-2011); Dana W. Sennett (Democrat, 2011); [[Karen Heck]] (independent, 2012-2014); Nicholas Isgro (Republican, 2015\u2013present).<ref>[http://www.waterville-me.gov/mayor/wp-content/uploads/sites/21/2017/06/History-of-Mayors-Rev-June-2017.pdf History of Mayors: Waterville, Maine, 1888 \u2014 Present], City of Waterville (revised June 2017).</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Isgro faced a [[recall election]] after he made a [[Twitter]] post mocking [[David Hogg (activist)|David Hogg]], a survivor of the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in [[Parkland, Florida]]. The recall effort was backed by former Mayor [[Karen Heck]], a Democrat who had previously endorsed Isgro. Isgro later made his Twitter feed private and said that he had deleted the post.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/1e22e50939304fd8b3f847b6ef299eaa|title=Mayor faces recall vote over tweet mocking shooting survivor|agency=Associated Press|date=2018-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/386183-gop-maine-mayor-facing-recall-vote-over-tweet-mocking-parkland-survivor|title=GOP Maine mayor facing recall vote over tweet mocking Parkland survivor|first=Avery|last=Anapol|date=4 May 2018|website=The Hill}}</ref> During the recall effort, Isgro asserted that outside interests and the City Council were plotting to oust him over disputes over the city budget and taxation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/05/12/waterville-mayor-says-council-wants-13-percent-tax-hike/|title=Waterville mayor says council wants 13 percent tax hike|author=Rachel Ohm|date=May 12, 2018|website=Morning Sentinel}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/06/07/nick-isgros-promise-to-veto-budget-challenged-by-waterville-officials-councilors/|title=Mayor Isgro's promise to veto budget challenged by Waterville officials, councilors|author=Rachel Ohm & Amy Calder|date=June 8, 2018|website=Morning Sentinel}}</ref> After an acrimonious recall campaign,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/05/07/waterville-mayor-nick-isgro-questions-integrity-of-recall-petition/|title=Waterville Mayor Nick Isgro questions integrity of recall petition|author=Rachel Ohm|date=May 5, 2018|website=Morning Sentinel}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/05/17/waterville-mayor-attempts-to-frame-recall-election-as-a-tax-issue|title=Waterville mayor attempts to frame recall election as a tax issue|author=Rachel Ohm|date=May 17, 2018|website=Central Maine Morning Sentinel}}</ref> Waterville voters narrowly defeated the recall attempt, with 1,563 \"no\" votes (51%) to 1,472 \"yes\" votes (49%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/06/13/waterville-mayor-asks-for-apology-reimbursement-after-surviving-recall-vote/|title=Waterville mayor asks for apology, reimbursement after surviving recall vote|author=Rachel Ohm|date=June 14, 2018|website=Morning Sentinel}}</ref>\n\n===Political makeup===\nWaterville is considered a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] stronghold in [[Maine's 1st congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kjonline.com/politics/Republican-Democratic-party-leaders-.html|title=National Republican, Democratic party leaders come to Maine|work=Central Maine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kjonline.com/news/new-numbers-old-story-in-2nd-district_2012-09-22.html|title=New numbers, old story in 2nd District Congressional race|work=Central Maine}}</ref> [[Barack Obama]] received 70% of Waterville's votes in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/news/politics/2008/election_results/me_president/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525213025/http://www.boston.com/news/politics/2008/election_results/me_president/ |archive-date=2012-05-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''Voter registration'''\n{| class=wikitable\n! colspan = 6 | Voter Registration and Party Enrollment as of June 2014<ref name=\"maine.gov voters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maine.gov/sos/cec/elec/r-e-active.pdf|title=Registered & Enrolled Voters - Statewide|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan = 2 | Party\n! Total Voters\n! Percentage\n|-\n{{party color|Democratic Party (United States)}}\n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| align = center | 4,562\n| align = center | 41.25%\n|-\n{{party color|Independent (United States)}}\n| Unenrolled\n| align = center | 4,200\n| align = center | 37.98%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n| [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| align = center | 1,940\n| align = center | 17.54%\n|-\n{{party color|Green Party (United States)}}\n| [[Maine Green Independent Party|Green Independent]]\n| align = center | 356\n| align = center | 3.21%\n|-\n! colspan = 2 | Total\n! align = center | 11,058\n! align = center | 100%\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n*[[Waterville Robert LaFleur Airport|Robert LaFleur Airport]]\n*[[Interstate 95 in Maine|Interstate 95]]\n*[[US Route 201]]\n*[[Maine State Route 100A|State Route 100A]]\n*[[Maine State Route 137|State Route 137]]\n*[[Maine State Route 32|State Route 32]]\n*[[Maine State Route 137 Business|State Route 137 Business]]\n*[[Maine State Route 11|State Route 11]]\n*[[Maine State Route 104|State Route 104]]\n*[[Pan Am Railways]]: Waterville Intermodal Facility<ref>[http://www.centralmaine.org/profile.shtml Central Maine Growth Council] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122095231/http://www.centralmaine.org/profile.shtml |date=November 22, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"fhwa\">{{Cite web|url=http://ops.fhwa.dot.gov/freight/freight_analysis/env_factors/env_fact_app_e2.htm|title=Appendix E &#8211; Waterville, Maine Intermodal Facility - Review of Environmental Factors - FHWA Freight Management and Operations|publisher=[[Federal Highway Administration]]|date=28 October 2009|accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Waterville Public Schools]] provides the city primary and secondary education. It was a part of [[Kennebec Valley Consolidated Schools]] (AOS92) from 2009 to 2018.<ref name=\"Home20180905\">[http://www.aos92.org/ Home]. [[Kennebec Valley Consolidated Schools]]. Retrieved on September 5, 2018. \"Waterville Central Office Office of the Superintendent 25 Messalonskee Avenue Waterville, Maine 04901-5437 [...] Winslow Central Office 20 Dean Street Winslow, Maine 04901-5437\"</ref>\n\n[[Kennebec Valley Community College]] in [[Fairfield, Maine|Fairfield]] is the local public [[Community colleges in the United States|community college]]. Colby College and Thomas College are private 4-year colleges located in the city. Colby is the second highest ranked liberal arts college in Maine, according to [[U.S. News & World Report Best Colleges Ranking|U.S. News]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/colby-college-2039|title=Colby College|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. News|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227040909/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/colby-college-2039|archive-date=2017-02-27|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nWaterville is the set location of Camp Firewood in the [[Netflix]] show ''[[Wet Hot American Summer: First Day of Camp]]''.\n\n==Media==\nWaterville is home to one daily newspaper, the ''[[Morning Sentinel]]'' and a weekly college newspaper, ''[[The Colby Echo]]''.<ref>''[http://colbyechonews.com/ The Colby Echo]''</ref> The city is also home to [[Fox Broadcasting Network|Fox]] affiliate [[WPFO]] and [[Daystar Television Network|Daystar]] rebroadcaster [[WFYW-LP]], both serving the [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] market, and to several radio stations, including Colby's [[WMHB]], [[country music|country]] [[WEBB]], [[adult standards]] [[WTVL]] and [[Maine Public Broadcasting Network|MPBN]] on 91.3 FM.\n\n==Sister cities==\n* {{flagdeco|Russia}} [[Kotlas]], [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]], Russia\n\n==Sites of interest==\n[[File:Civil War Union Army monument, Waterville, ME IMG_2641.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Monument to [[Union Army]] soldiers in Waterville]]\n[[File:Waterville CC 02.jpg|thumb|200px|right5|Waterville Country Club golf course]]\n* [[Colby College]]\n* [[Colby College Museum of Art]]<ref>[http://www.colby.edu/museum Colby College Museum of Art]</ref>\n* [[Thomas College]]<ref>[http://www.thomas.edu/ Thomas College]</ref>\n* Atlantic Music Festival<ref>[http://www.atlanticmusicfestival.org/ Atlantic Music Festival]</ref>\n* [[Maine International Film Festival]]\n*[[Old Waterville High School]]\n*[[Old Waterville Post Office]]\n* [[Perkins Arboretum]]\n* Waterville Historical Society - [[Redington Museum]]<ref>[http://www.redingtonmuseum.org/ Waterville Historical Society - Redington Museum]</ref>\n* [[Waterville Public Library]]\n* Waterville Opera House<ref>[http://www.operahouse.org Waterville Opera House]</ref>\n* Waterville Main Street<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071230021208/http://www.watervillemainstreet.org/ Waterville Main Street]</ref>\n* Waterville - Winslow Footbridge ([[Two Cent Bridge]])\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of people from Waterville, Maine}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of mayors of Waterville, Maine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{AmCyc Poster|Waterville}}\n{{wikivoyage|Waterville (Maine)}}\n* [http://www.waterville-me.gov/ City of Waterville official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061009225841/http://www.waterville.lib.me.us/ Waterville Public Library]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071230021208/http://www.watervillemainstreet.org/ Waterville Main Street]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060906033215/http://morningsentinel.mainetoday.com/ ''Morning Sentinel'', Waterville's newspaper]\n* [[Maine Public Broadcasting Network]] featured Waterville in its [http://www.mainepublicradio.org/hometown/ Hometown Economies].{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} The video of that show is available [https://web.archive.org/web/20061004153717/http://www.mainepublicradio.org/hometown/waterville.html here].\n\n{{Kennebec County, Maine}}\n{{MELargestCities}}\n{{Maine}}\n{{Kennebec River}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Waterville, Maine| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Kennebec County, Maine]]\n[[Category:Cities in Maine]]\n[[Category:Micropolitan areas of Maine]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1802]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "XavierYZay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:The article indicated that Coburn Classical Institute merged with Oak Grove School and closed in \"the 1980s.\" I changed it to indicate that the merged school closed in 1989. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coburn_Classical_Institute and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/River_Meetinghouse.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waterville,_Maine"}
{"title_page": "Kid Boots", "text_new": "{{about|the musical|the film|Kid Boots (film)}}\n{{Infobox Musical\t\n|name= Kid Boots\n|subtitle=\n|image= Kidboots.jpg\n|caption= Sheet music cover (cropped)\n|music= [[Harry Tierney]]\n|lyrics= [[Joseph McCarthy (lyricist)|Joseph McCarthy]]\n|book= [[William Anthony McGuire]] and [[Otto Harbach]]\n|productions= 1923 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n|awards= \n}}\n\n'''''Kid Boots''''' is a [[musical theatre|musical]] with a book by [[William Anthony McGuire]] and [[Otto Harbach]], music by [[Harry Tierney]], and lyrics by [[Joseph McCarthy (lyricist)|Joseph McCarthy]].  The show was staged by [[Edward Royce]].\n \nProduced by [[Florenz Ziegfeld]], the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production, opened on December 31, 1923 at the [[Earl Carroll Theatre]] and then moved to the [[Selwyn Theatre]], where it ended on February 21, 1925,<ref>The New York Times, February 23, 1925</ref> for a total of 489 performances. The cast starred [[Eddie Cantor]] and [[Mary Eaton]], with [[George Olsen]] and his orchestra.\n\nThe show was billed as \u201cA Musical Comedy of Palm Beach and Golf\u201d and was set at the [[Everglades Club]] in [[Palm Beach, Florida]]. It was a showcase for Eddie Cantor, who played the caddie master at the swank club.  He gives golf lessons on the side, with crooked balls so the clients need more instruction.  He's also a bootlegger and a busybody.  He can't be fired, however, because he has something on everyone at the club. The most famous song to come out of the show was \u201cDinah\u201d by Sam M. Lewis, Joe Young and Harry Akst, added to the finale during the run for Eddie. The song later gave vocalist [[Dinah Shore]], discovered by Eddie Cantor in 1940, her stage name and the theme song for her long running radio and television shows.\n\nThe New York Times reported that on closing night, \"[j]ust before the finale, George Olsen's band marched down the aisle and serenaded the company, ending with 'Auld Lang Syne.' \"<ref>The New York Times, February 23, 1925</ref>\n\n==Film versions==\nDuring the run in New York City, inventor [[Lee DeForest]] filmed Cantor in the [[Phonofilm|DeForest Phonofilm]] [[sound-on-film]] process, in a short film known as ''[[A Few Moments with Eddie Cantor|A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of \"Kid Boots\"]]''. In 1926, [[Paramount Pictures]] released a [[Kid Boots (film)|feature film version]] directed by [[Frank Tuttle]], and starring Cantor, [[Clara Bow]], and [[Billie Dove]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017028/ IMDB entry]</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n{{col-begin}}{{col-2}}\nAct I      \n* A Day at the Club\n* The Social Observer\n* When Your Heart's in the Game\n* Keep Your Eye on the Ball\n* The Same Old Way\n* Someone Loves You after All (The Rain Song)\n* The Intruder Dance\n* We've Got to Have More\n* Polly Put the Kettle On\n* Let's Do and Say We Didn't (Let's Don't and Say We Did)\n* In the Swim at Miami\n* Along the Old Lake Trail\n* On With the Game\n{{col-break}}\nAct II      \n* (Since Ma Is Playing) Mah Jong (by [[Billy Rose]] and [[Con Conrad]])\n* Bet on the One You Fancy\n* I'm In My Glory\n* Play Fair, Man!\n* Win for Me\n* The Cake Eater's Ball\n* Down \u2018Round the 19th Hole\n* En Route\n* When the Cocoanuts Call\n* In the Rough\n* That\u2019s All There Is\n{{col-end}}\n\nAlso interpolated into the show:\n* If You Do What You Do (by Roy Turk, Lou Handman and Eddie Cantor)\n* He\u2019s the Hottest Man in Town (by [[Owen Murphy]] and [[Jay Gorney]])\n* [[Alabamy Bound]] (words by [[Bud DeSylva]] and [[Bud Green]], music by [[Ray Henderson]])\n* [[Dinah (song)|Dinah]] (by [[Sam M. Lewis]], [[Joe Young (lyricist)|Joe Young]] and [[Harry Akst]])\n\n==See also==\n*''[[A Few Moments with Eddie Cantor|A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of \"Kid Boots\"]]'' (1923) short film made in the sound-on-film [[Phonofilm]] process, with Cantor performing an excerpt of ''Kid Boots''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=9452 ''Kid Boots'' at Internet Broadway Database]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0014886/ ''A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of 'Kid Boots''' (1923) at IMDB]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017028/ ''Kid Boots'' (1926 film version) at IMDB]\n\n[[Category:1923 musicals]]\n[[Category:Broadway musicals]]\n[[Category:Musicals set in the Roaring Twenties]]\n[[Category:Musicals by Otto Harbach]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the musical|the film|Kid Boots (film)}}\n{{Infobox Musical\t\n|name= Kid Boots\n|subtitle=\n|image= Kidboots.jpg\n|caption= Sheet music cover (cropped)\n|music= [[Harry Tierney]]\n|lyrics= [[Joseph McCarthy (lyricist)|Joseph McCarthy]]\n|book= [[William Anthony McGuire]] and [[Otto Harbach]]\n|productions= 1923 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n|awards= \n}}\n\n'''''Kid Boots''''' is a [[musical theatre|musical]] with a book by [[William Anthony McGuire]] and [[Otto Harbach]], music by [[Harry Tierney]], and lyrics by [[Joseph McCarthy (lyricist)|Joseph McCarthy]].  The show was staged by [[Edward Royce]].\n \nProduced by [[Florenz Ziegfeld]], the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production, opened on December 31, 1923 at the [[Earl Carroll Theatre]] and then moved to the [[Selwyn Theatre]], where it ended on February 21, 1925,<ref>The New York Times, February 23, 1925</ref> for a total of 489 performances. The cast starred [[Eddie Cantor]] and [[Mary Eaton]], with [[George Olsen]] and his orchestra. \n\nThe show was billed as \u201cA Musical Comedy of Palm Beach and Golf\u201d and was set at the [[Everglades Club]] in [[Palm Beach, Florida]]. It was a showcase for Eddie Cantor, who played the caddie master at the swank club.  He gives golf lessons on the side, with crooked balls so the clients need more instruction.  He\u2019s also a bootlegger and a busybody.  He can\u2019t be fired, however, because he has something on everyone at the club. The most famous song to come out of the show was \u201cDinah\u201d by Sam M. Lewis, Joe Young and Harry Akst, added to the finale during the run for Eddie. The song later gave vocalist [[Dinah Shore]], discovered by Eddie Cantor in 1940, her stage name and the theme song for her long running radio and television shows.\n\nThe New York Times reported that on closing night, \"[j]ust before the finale, George Olsen's band marched down the aisle and serenaded the company, ending with 'Auld Lang Syne.' \"<ref>The New York Times, February 23, 1925</ref>\n\n==Film versions==\nDuring the run in New York City, inventor [[Lee DeForest]] filmed Cantor in the [[Phonofilm|DeForest Phonofilm]] [[sound-on-film]] process, in a short film known as ''[[A Few Moments with Eddie Cantor|A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of \"Kid Boots\"]]''. In 1926, [[Paramount Pictures]] released a [[Kid Boots (film)|feature film version]] directed by [[Frank Tuttle]], and starring Cantor, [[Clara Bow]], and [[Billie Dove]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017028/ IMDB entry]</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n{{col-begin}}{{col-2}}\nAct I      \n* A Day at the Club\n* The Social Observer\n* When Your Heart\u2019s in the Game\n* Keep Your Eye on the Ball\n* The Same Old Way\n* Someone Loves You after All (The Rain Song)\n* The Intruder Dance\n* We've Got to Have More\n* Polly Put the Kettle On\n* Let\u2019s Do and Say We Didn\u2019t (Let's Don't and Say We Did)\n* In the Swim at Miami\n* Along the Old Lake Trail\n* On With the Game\n{{col-break}}\nAct II      \n* (Since Ma Is Playing) Mah Jong (by [[Billy Rose]] and [[Con Conrad]])\n* Bet on the One You Fancy\n* I\u2019m In My Glory\n* Play Fair, Man!\n* Win for Me\n* The Cake Eater\u2019s Ball\n* Down \u2018Round the 19th Hole\n* En Route\n* When the Cocoanuts Call\n* In the Rough\n* That\u2019s All There Is\n{{col-end}}\n\nAlso interpolated into the show:\n* If You Do What You Do (by Roy Turk, Lou Handman and Eddie Cantor)\n* He\u2019s the Hottest Man in Town (by [[Owen Murphy]] and [[Jay Gorney]])\n* [[Alabamy Bound]] (words by [[Bud DeSylva]] and [[Bud Green]], music by [[Ray Henderson]])\n* [[Dinah (song)|Dinah]] (by [[Sam M. Lewis]], [[Joe Young (lyricist)|Joe Young]] and [[Harry Akst]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[A Few Moments with Eddie Cantor|A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of \"Kid Boots\"]]'' (1923) short film made in the sound-on-film [[Phonofilm]] process, with Cantor performing an excerpt of ''Kid Boots''\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=9452 ''Kid Boots'' at Internet Broadway Database]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0014886/ ''A Few Moments With Eddie Cantor, Star of 'Kid Boots''' (1923) at IMDB]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017028/ ''Kid Boots'' (1926 film version) at IMDB]\n\n\n[[Category:1923 musicals]]\n[[Category:Broadway musicals]]\n[[Category:Musicals set in the Roaring Twenties]]\n[[Category:Musicals by Otto Harbach]]\n", "name_user": "Loriendrew", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: can\u2019t \u2192 can't (2), He\u2019s \u2192 He's, I\u2019m \u2192 I'm, \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kid_Boots"}
{"title_page": "Fran\u00e7ois Audouy", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Fran\u00e7ois Audouy\n| image       = Production Designer Fran\u00e7ois Audouy.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Audouy speaking at the 2019 Camp conference in Calgary, Alberta, Canada\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Toulouse, France]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Production Designer\n| yearsactive = 2002\u2013present\n| height      = \n| spouse      = Veronique Audouy (1998\u2013present)\n| children    = 2\n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| website     = {{URL|http://www.audouy.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Audouy''' ({{IPA-fr|odwi|lang}}; born June 17, 1974) is a French-American movie [[production designer]] and [[art director]]. He is a frequent collaborator with director [[James Mangold]], having designed ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]]'' (2013) its sequel ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' (2016), and ''[[Ford v. Ferrari|Ford v Ferrari]]'' (2019). Other design credits include the period fantasy films ''[[Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter]]'' (2012) and ''[[Dracula Untold]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news | last=Cieply | first=Michael | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/10/movies/abraham-lincoln-vampire-hunter-rewrites-history.html?_r=3&ref=arts | title=Aside from the vampires, Abraham Lincoln film seeks accuracy | work=New York Times | publisher=[[nytimes.com]] | date=May 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe has worked as an art director for directors [[Michael Bay]], [[Tim Burton]], [[Martin Campbell]], [[Robert Redford]], [[Zack Snyder]], and [[Steven Spielberg]].\n\nHe has also designed music videos for [[Harry Styles]], [[Camila Cabello]] and [[Dua Lipa]].\n\n==Early life==\nAudouy was born in [[Toulouse]], [[France]], to a [[France|French]] father and an [[England|English]] mother. He is a bi-lingual speaker of [[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]].\n\nHe moved to [[Southern California]] at the age of six after his parents divorced and his mother remarried.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;Production designer\n* ''[[Ghostbusters 2020|Ghostbusters: Afterlife]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Ford v Ferrari]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Dracula (2014 film)|Dracula Untold]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter (film)|Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter]]'' (2012)\n{{Col-break}}\n;Art director\n* ''[[Green Lantern (film)|Green Lantern]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Lions for Lambs]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'' (2005)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Awards ==\n\n*2019: Nominated for an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Period Film category,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-nominations-2020-complete-list-1260655|title=Art Directors Guild nominations 2020|last=|first=|date=9 December 2019|website=Hollywood Reporter|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Satellite Awards|Satellite Award]] for Best Art Direction & Production Design for [[Ford v Ferrari|Ford v. Ferrari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/12/03/24th-satellite-awards-announce-nominations-ford-v-ferrari-leads-the-way/|title=Satellite award nominations|last=|first=|date=|website=Awards Circuit|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204055814/https://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/12/03/24th-satellite-awards-announce-nominations-ford-v-ferrari-leads-the-way/|archive-date=2019-12-04|access-date=}}</ref>\n*2018: Won an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Contemporary Film category for [[Logan (film)|Logan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adg.org/sites/art/information/Press-Releases-2018/ADG_AWARDS_Nominations_2018.pdf|title=ADG awards press release|website=Art Directors Guild|access-date=2018-01-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518083035/https://www.adg.org/sites/art/information/Press-Releases-2018/ADG_AWARDS_Nominations_2018.pdf|archive-date=2018-05-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*2005: Nominated for an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Period or Fantasy Film category for his work as Art Director on [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.audouy.com/ Fran\u00e7ois Audouy Official Site]\n*{{IMDb name|0002885}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Audouy, Francois}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American production designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Toulouse]]\n[[Category:French film designers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Fran\u00e7ois Audouy\n| image       = Production Designer Fran\u00e7ois Audouy.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Audouy speaking at the 2019 Camp conference in Calgary, Alberta, Canada\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Toulouse, France]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = Production Designer\n| yearsactive = 2002\u2013present\n| height      = \n| spouse      = Veronique Audouy (1998\u2013present)\n| children    = 2\n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| website     = {{URL|http://www.audouy.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Fran\u00e7ois Audouy''' ({{IPA-fr|odwi|lang}}; born June 17, 1974) is a French-American movie [[production designer]] and [[art director]]. He is a frequent collaborator with director [[James Mangold]], having designed ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]]'' (2013) its sequel ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' (2016), and ''[[Ford v. Ferrari|Ford v Ferrari]]'' (2019). He also designed the period fantasy films ''[[Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter]]'' (2012) and ''[[Dracula Untold]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news | last=Cieply | first=Michael | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/10/movies/abraham-lincoln-vampire-hunter-rewrites-history.html?_r=3&ref=arts | title=Aside from the vampires, Abraham Lincoln film seeks accuracy | work=New York Times | publisher=[[nytimes.com]] | date=May 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe has worked as an art director for directors [[Michael Bay]], [[Tim Burton]], [[Martin Campbell]], [[Robert Redford]], [[Zack Snyder]], and [[Steven Spielberg]].\n\nHe has also designed music videos for [[Harry Styles]], [[Camila Cabello]] and [[Dua Lipa]].\n\n==Early life==\nAudouy was born in [[Toulouse]], [[France]], to a [[France|French]] father and an [[England|English]] mother. He is a bi-lingual speaker of [[French language|French]] and [[English language|English]].\n\nHe moved to [[Southern California]] at the age of six after his parents divorced and his mother remarried.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;Production designer\n* ''[[Ghostbusters 2020|Ghostbusters: Afterlife]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Ford v Ferrari]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Dracula (2014 film)|Dracula Untold]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter (film)|Abraham Lincoln: Vampire Hunter]]'' (2012)\n{{Col-break}}\n;Art director\n* ''[[Green Lantern (film)|Green Lantern]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Lions for Lambs]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'' (2005)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Awards ==\n\n*2019: Nominated for an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Period Film category,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/art-directors-guild-nominations-2020-complete-list-1260655|title=Art Directors Guild nominations 2020|last=|first=|date=9 December 2019|website=Hollywood Reporter|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Satellite Awards|Satellite Award]] for Best Art Direction & Production Design for [[Ford v Ferrari|Ford v. Ferrari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/12/03/24th-satellite-awards-announce-nominations-ford-v-ferrari-leads-the-way/|title=Satellite award nominations|last=|first=|date=|website=Awards Circuit|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204055814/https://www.awardscircuit.com/2019/12/03/24th-satellite-awards-announce-nominations-ford-v-ferrari-leads-the-way/|archive-date=2019-12-04|access-date=}}</ref>\n*2018: Won an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Contemporary Film category for [[Logan (film)|Logan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adg.org/sites/art/information/Press-Releases-2018/ADG_AWARDS_Nominations_2018.pdf|title=ADG awards press release|website=Art Directors Guild|access-date=2018-01-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518083035/https://www.adg.org/sites/art/information/Press-Releases-2018/ADG_AWARDS_Nominations_2018.pdf|archive-date=2018-05-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*2005: Nominated for an [[Art Directors Guild]] [[ADG Excellence in Production Design Award|production design award]] in the Period or Fantasy Film category for his work as Art Director on [[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]].\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.audouy.com/ Fran\u00e7ois Audouy Official Site]\n*{{IMDb name|0002885}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Audouy, Francois}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American production designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Toulouse]]\n[[Category:French film designers]]\n", "name_user": "Rennarc", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Audouy"}
{"title_page": "Jay Paley House", "text_new": "The '''Jay Paley House''' is a house at 1060 Brooklawn Drive, in [[Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]. It was designed by [[Paul Williams (architect)|Paul R. Williams]] for businessman Jacob Jay Paley (1885-1960) and his wife Lilian (1893-1954). It was built in 1935 on a six-acre estate.<ref name=\"Watters2007\"/>\n\n==Background==\nJay Paley, and his brother Samuel, were Russian immigrants who had founded the Congress Cigar Company, manufacturers of the [[La Palina]] brand, in Chicago in the 1890s.<ref name='PCAD'>{{cite web|title=Paley, Jay, House, Holmby Hills, Los Angeles, CA|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/building/2955/|work=Pacific Coast Architecture Database|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Paley family founded the [[Columbia Broacasting System]] (CBS) and Paley subsequently sold a substantial shareholding in CBS in 1928 for several million dollars. Paley became a film producer in the early 1930s and in 1934 founded JayPay Productions with film executive [[Walter Wanger]] in association with [[Paramount Studios]] in 1934. Payley sold further CBS shares to Samuel Paley, his brother, and his nephew [[William S. Paley]] to finance his film production company. Paley and his wife Lillian moved to Los Angeles, and the house was commissioned.<ref name=\"Hyland2008\">{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Hyland|title=The Legendary Estates of Beverly Hills|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KaX6KwAACAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Random House Incorporated|isbn=978-0-8478-3162-3}}</ref> Paley subsequently invested in the [[Arrowhead Springs, San Bernardino, California#Arrowhead Springs Hotel and Spa|Arrowhead Springs Hotel]] which was also designed by Williams.\n\nWilliams had previously designed a house for Jay Paley's nephew, [[William S. Paley]], at 200 South Mapleton Drive that was completed in 1934. Writing in The Legendary Estates of Beverly Hills, Jeffrey Hyland felt that the house marked a 'new direction' for Williams as he 'He started with the traditional English Georgian style and then gave the residence a thoroughly modernist spirit, creating a residence that was both traditional and contemporary'.<ref name=\"Hyland2008\"/> The style of the house has also been described as Hollywood Regency and English Georgian.<ref name='PCAD'/><ref name=\"Watters2007\"/>\nThe furnishings of the house were sold at auction after Paley's death in 1961 and the estate sold for $475,000 ({{Inflation|US|475000|1961|r=0|fmt=eq|cursign=US}}).<ref name=\"Watters2007\">{{cite book|author=Sam Watters|title=Houses of Los Angeles: 1920-1935|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qi03AQAAIAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Acanthus Press|pages=44\u201353}}</ref> The house was subsequently bought by the businessman [[Barron Hilton]].<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\n==Design==\nThe two storey brick house is designed as a modified H-plan.<ref name='PCAD'/> The northwest and southwest wings and center are extended to form an E-configuration from the flat facade. The entrance door is framed with wooden columns and a pediment. The rear of the house also has extended northeast and southwest wings, with a two-storey conical roof supported by columns summouting the semicircular southeast wing. A central hall runs the entire length of the house from north to south. A large living room is to the right, it opens to a small garden and ornamental pond. The first floor is the site of the music room and the library. The east side of the house contains the dining room, a breakfast room, and four maids rooms with a separate living room. A private garden for the servants is located next to the [[service wing]].<ref name=\"Hyland2008\"/> The house was built by the building contractors O'Neal and Sons.<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\nThe interior of the house was designed by Harriet R. Shellenberger, her interior designs were removed in 1961 following Paley's death.<ref name='PCAD'/> The interior was redesigned by Kathryn Crawford in the 1960s; Crawford's designs for the house were featured in ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' in September 1968.<ref name='USM'>{{cite web|title=Paul Williams|url=https://usmodernist.org/pwilliams.htm|work=US Modernist|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe swimming pool and the pool house precede the main house and were designed by Williams to a Classical design with landscape architect c.1932 and built by the Paddock Pool Complex.  The pool house contains a bar and grill and games room. The success of the swimming complex convinced palsy to commission the main house from Williams. The pool is known as the Zodiac pool. The bottom of the pool features the 12 [[signs of the Zodiac]] in blue, yellow and gold tiles imported from France with a sunburst design.<ref name=\"Publications2002\">{{cite book|author=Home Buyer Publications|title=Old House Interiors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zAEAAAAMBAJ|date=July 2002|publisher=Home Buyer Publications|page=78}}</ref><ref name=\"Cardinal-Pett2015\">{{cite book|author=Clare Cardinal-Pett|title=A History of Architecture and Urbanism in the Americas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Yr4CgAAQBAJ|date=19 November 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-43125-1|page=449}}</ref>\nThe pool house was featured on the cover of ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' in 1933.<ref name='PCAD'/> The house cost $100,000 to build ({{Inflation|US|100000|1935|r=0|fmt=eq|cursign=US}}).<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|California}}\n\n[[Category:Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1935]]\n[[Category:Houses in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Paul Williams (architect) buildings]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Jay Paley House''' is a house at 1060 Brooklawn Drive, in [[Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]. It was designed by [[Paul Williams (architect)|Paul R. Williams]] for businessman Jacob Jay Paley (1885-1960) and his wife Lilian (1893-1954). It was built in 1935 on a six-acre estate.<ref name=\"Watters2007\"/>\n\n==Background==\nJay Paley, and his brother Samuel, were Russian immigrants who had founded the Congress Cigar Company, manufacturers of the [[La Palina]] brand, in Chicago in the 1890s.<ref name='PCAD'>{{cite web|title=Paley, Jay, House, Holmby Hills, Los Angeles, CA|url=http://pcad.lib.washington.edu/building/2955/|work=Pacific Coast Architecture Database|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Paley family founded the [[Columbia Broacasting System]] (CBS) and Paley subsequently sold a substantial shareholding in CBS in 1928 for several million dollars. Paley became a film producer in the early 1930s and in 1934 founded JayPay Productions with film executive [[Walter Wanger]] in association with [[Paramount Studios]] in 1934. Payley sold further CBS shares to Samuel Paley, his brother, and his nephew [[William S. Paley]] to finance his film production company. Paley and his wife Lillian moved to Los Angeles, and the house was commissioned.<ref name=\"Hyland2008\">{{cite book|author=Jeffrey Hyland|title=The Legendary Estates of Beverly Hills|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KaX6KwAACAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Random House Incorporated|isbn=978-0-8478-3162-3}}</ref> Paley subsequently invested in the [[Arrowhead Springs, San Bernardino, California#Arrowhead Springs Hotel and Spa|Arrowhead Springs Hotel]] which was also designed by Williams.\n\nWilliams had previously designed a house for Jay Paley's nephew, [[William S. Paley]], at 200 South Mapleton Drive that was completed in 1934. Writing in The Legendary Estates of Beverly Hills, Jeffrey Hyland felt that the house marked a 'new direction' for Williams as he 'He started with the traditional English Georgian style and then gave the residence a thoroughly modernist spirit, creating a residence that was both traditional and contemporary'.<ref name=\"Hyland2008\"/> The style of the house has also been described as Hollywood Regency and English Georgian.<ref name='PCAD'/><ref name=\"Watters2007\"/>\nThe furnishings of the house were sold at auction after Paley's death in 1961 and the estate sold for $ 475,000 ({{Inflation|US|475000|1961|r=0|fmt=eq|cursign=US}}).<ref name=\"Watters2007\">{{cite book|author=Sam Watters|title=Houses of Los Angeles: 1920-1935|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qi03AQAAIAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Acanthus Press|pages=44\u201353}}</ref> The house was subsequently bought by the businessman [[Barron Hilton]].<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\n==Design==\nThe two storey brick house is designed as a modified H-plan.<ref name='PCAD'/> The northwest and southwest wings and center are extended to form an E-configuration from the flat facade. The entrance door is framed with wooden columns and a pediment. The rear of the house also has extended northeast and southwest wings, with a two-storey conical roof supported by columns summouting the semicircular southeast wing. A central hall runs the entire length of the house from north to south. A large living room is to the right, it opens to a small garden and ornamental pond. The first floor is the site of the music room and the library. The east side of the house contains the dining room, a breakfast room, and four maids rooms with a separate living room. A private garden for the servants is located next to the [[service wing]].<ref name=\"Hyland2008\"/> The house was built by the building contractors O'Neal and Sons.<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\nThe interior of the house was designed by Harriet R. Shellenberger, her interior designs were removed in 1961 following Paley's death.<ref name='PCAD'/> The interior was redesigned by Kathryn Crawford in the 1960s; Crawford's designs for the house were featured in ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' in September 1968.<ref name='USM'>{{cite web|title=Paul Williams|url=https://usmodernist.org/pwilliams.htm|work=US Modernist|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe swimming pool and the pool house precede the main house and were designed by Williams to a Classical design with landscape architect c.1932 and built by the Paddock Pool Complex.  The pool house contains a bar and grill and games room. The success of the swimming complex convinced palsy to commission the main house from Williams. The pool is known as the Zodiac pool. The bottom of the pool features the 12 [[signs of the Zodiac]] in blue, yellow and gold tiles imported from France with a sunburst design.<ref name=\"Publications2002\">{{cite book|author=Home Buyer Publications|title=Old House Interiors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zAEAAAAMBAJ|date=July 2002|publisher=Home Buyer Publications|page=78}}</ref><ref name=\"Cardinal-Pett2015\">{{cite book|author=Clare Cardinal-Pett|title=A History of Architecture and Urbanism in the Americas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Yr4CgAAQBAJ|date=19 November 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-43125-1|page=449}}</ref>\nThe pool house was featured on the cover of ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' in 1933.<ref name='PCAD'/> The house cost $100,000 to build ({{Inflation|US|100000|1935|r=0|fmt=eq|cursign=US}}).<ref name='PCAD'/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|California}}\n\n[[Category:Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1935]]\n[[Category:Houses in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Paul Williams (architect) buildings]]\n", "name_user": "No Swan So Fine", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Paley_House"}
